The first lawsuit from the Cousteau Society came in 1995, when Jacques and Francine sued Jean-Michel over the name of his Fiji ecotourism resort: The Cousteau Fiji Islands Resort. 

Jacques claimed the resort was damaging his image. 

… https://t.co/NJKLnbm1aN

Longtime associates soured on the society with Francine’s ascent, and many left, including Jacques’ son Jean-Michel in 1992. 

https://t.co/dpLn5mexGe https://t.co/uveN54inl0

A bitter feud emerged between Cousteau’s first family and his second — one that worsened after Jacque’s death, when Francine became president of the Cousteau Society. 

https://t.co/dpLn5mexGe https://t.co/1BX0Wxn6Tz

But behind the scenes, his life was messier. While he was married to his first wife, Simone, he and Francine carried on an affair, secretly having two of their own children. 

They married shortly after Simone died of cancer in 1990. 

https://t.co/dpLn5mexGe

Jacques was one of the most beloved men in the world, a respected documentarian, TV host, and the so-called father of scuba diving, thanks to his invention of the Aqua-Lung, the first modern apparatus for breathing underwater.

https://t.co/dpLn5mexGe https://t.co/4DjxcdNb5t

In 1995, Jacques quietly shifted his assets to the Cousteau Society, giving the nonprofit total control over his film archive, royalties, and intellectual property. The nonprofit has since filed a half dozen suits in the US against other Cousteaus. 

https://t.co/dpLn5mexGe

Because the name “Cousteau” is considered intellectual property, the family may use it to brand their own enterprises only if they include their first name in the same font and color, and size it to either the same or up to twice as large as the surname.… https://t.co/k49K0Ae7k4

Jacques’ children and grandchildren are limited in how they can discuss him to promote their own nonprofit or business ventures. Some have been sued for making announcements on June 11 (his birthday) or writing about their memories with him.

https://t.co/dpLn5mexGe

⚡️ “Space Force started as a national joke. Now it's seen as Donald Trump's best idea.” by @thisisinsider 

https://t.co/Hh749Qonnn

Now that Biden has embraced the Space Force, the branch has become an established part of the national-security apparatus. 

Read the full story from @adamwren. ⬇️

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

In 2017, the Democrat-led House passed a bill to carve a space corps out of existing Air Force resources and personnel. 

But the Air Force opposed the measure and it fizzled in the Senate. 

It took Trump's embrace of the idea to make it a reality. 

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

The conceptual roots for the Space Force go back to the Cold War. 

The idea began gaining momentum in 2001, when Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld warned of “a space Pearl Harbor.”

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

Even after Trump became serious about creating a Space Force, he seemed to picture missiles on Mars (“Space is a warfighting domain,” he liked to say), not the crucial but more mundane things that the Space Force does today, Wren says.

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

The Space Force is a subset of the Air Force. It has 13,600 members, split between 6,900 military personnel and 6,700 civilians. 

At its peak, a spokesperson said, it expected to top out at about 16,000 — by far the smallest branch of the Armed Forces.

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

It means monitoring and flying US military satellites that give GPS to the world, detecting missile launches around the globe, and keeping an eye on orbiting space junk to make sure it doesn’t collide with anything important. 

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn https://t.co/lc7KtSt7zY

The Space Force says its mission is to “defend our nation and its freedom to operate in space.” In practice, this has nothing to do with shooting down unidentified aerial objects or establishing a base on the moon.

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

It's also being taken seriously by foreign-policy experts who say it could wind up playing a pivotal but classified role in Ukraine. 

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn https://t.co/H4PEBtxOrO

Now, the branch is a force to be reckoned with. 

Space Force leader Gen. John Raymond is one of Biden's top military advisors. 

It has professionalized its operations, issuing a formal doctrine defining space power as its own kind of military might. 

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

The Space Force was a laughingstock from the moment Trump announced it. 

He spoke about the Space Force — the first new branch of the armed forces in 73 years — like it was a gee-wiz idea he dreamed up in the shower, Wren writes.

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

Season two of the satire, which premiered Feb. 18, continues to be a case of art imitating life, as Gen. Mark Naird (Carell) and his team "try to prove their worth to a new presidential administration."

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

Netflix's comedy "Space Force," starring Steve Carell, debuted in May 2020, five months after the actual Space Force was signed into existence by President  Trump. 

Thompson and his colleagues made time to watch their fictional counterparts on Netflix.
… https://t.co/TUDem0uvW5

Gen. David Thompson, the second-in-command of the US Space Force, is in on the jokes about his day job. 

But two years into its creation, it has managed to go from national farce to a force to be reckoned with in Washington, @adamwren writes. ⬇️ 

https://t.co/o9B1JLhpbn

Snowmaking for the Winter Games might require 500 million gallons of water, according to one estimate.  https://t.co/Ur2Hy1h7x9 https://t.co/u9j2XwVMJG

The main skiing venues are in a parched part of China that gets just 25 inches of average annual snowfall — not nearly enough to cover the slopes. 

By comparison, Park City, Utah gets 235 inches. It’s where Salt Lake City’s Olympic giant slalom was held. https://t.co/Ur2Hy1h7x9
And some costs aren’t as obvious to tally, like the human and environmental ones. @AFP reported that farmers were forced from their land to make way for solar energy. https://t.co/XajoQ0Uc41

Beijing did not respond to questions about infrastructure or sport-related investments like new venues. 

Without those answers, it’s likely we'll never get a full understanding of what the Winter Games cost in 2022. https://t.co/Ur2Hy1h7x9 https://t.co/emyVPVgfSh

There are three brand-new Olympic villages that were built to house the athletes, with just one ringing in at about $3.2 billion.

The International Olympic Committee told Insider that the official budget doesn’t include infrastructure costs.
https://t.co/EVpR4bDMnd

Beijing spent $205.6 million to spruce up one of the region’s airports and $773.5 million on a new subway line. 

China is also finishing up a $15 billion highway project to connect venues in Yanqing and Zhangjiakou. https://t.co/Ur2Hy1h7x9 https://t.co/MBYx4UuK6h

We found major infrastructure costs related to the 2022 Olympics, like a brand new bullet train that links all three host cities, which rang in at $9.2 billion. It cuts the travel time between Beijing and Zhangjiakou from 3 hours to just under an hour. https://t.co/yvCZbMoV5k

Beijing’s official tally of $3.9 billion looks especially low when you consider that no Games since London have cost less than $13 billion. 

That's because the official budget includes very little beyond the costs of running the 19-day event. … https://t.co/QqOlgAwAI4

Behind headlines of sustainability and savings is a catalog of spending that could actually land Beijing among the most expensive games in history.
https://t.co/e2QKeKMCML

Beijing says the cost of hosting the @Olympics is among the cheapest ever at $3.9 billion, but the true cost might be 10 times that.

⚡️ “CDC Director Rochelle Walensky reflects on the challenges she's faced as a leader and what the agency could do better” by @thisisinsider 

https://t.co/FkLWp1gH26

To read more of Dr. Rochelle Walensky's honest look back at her first year as the leader of the CDC, subscribe to @thisisinsider. 👇

https://t.co/FnheoELSzY

Still, the CDC has made a huge amount of progress just in the last year. And Walensky has the support of her agency, family and network to keep her afloat. 

https://t.co/FnheoELSzY https://t.co/GSYUDDraME

In her time as CDC director, Walensky has experienced a new level of vitriol. 

She says she — and other figures, like Dr. Anthony Fauci — are "easy targets" for people who are unhappy during the pandemic. 

https://t.co/bWndkT8sjm https://t.co/pQ3PUXwxRF

But she says the CDC's data-modernization efforts have offered windows into so many things that we couldn't see before.

Poop tracking, for one, is the future of COVID surveillance, she says — and disease tracking in general. 

https://t.co/h4HnmrgSNb

Walensky also said she isn't thinking about post-omicron guidance yet. 

Her crisis "barometer" still has her on high alert. 

https://t.co/FnheoELSzY https://t.co/25cQko5CZg

Walensky understands that the CDC's guidelines have been confusing, but she stands by them. 

The agency's responsibility, she said, is to communicate complex science as it's evolving, though it could do better at expressing that. 

… https://t.co/nyXonQrDLB

Walensky says she likes hearing dissenting opinions when making decisions, but it's hard to make time for that in a fast-moving pandemic.

A hallmark of her leadership style is fostering relationships, but that’s harder right now.

… https://t.co/xV7MOWYr76

Historically, she said, the CDC has had a reputation of dotting every I and crossing every T. But she says it is working on that speed — and it has made good progress. 

https://t.co/FnheoELSzY https://t.co/BqRmR3dqyb

It hasn't been the smoothest road.

Walensky acknowledged that the CDC was still "working to adapt" its pandemic response. 

But she also said that the agency deserved some serious credit for its moves toward becoming nimbler and more modern.

https://t.co/FnheoELSzY

When Walensky started, the vaccination push was off to a rocky start and federal data on the virus was next to nonexistent.

Now, though #COVID19 is still very much with us, the CDC has upped its data tracking and booster shots are widely available.

https://t.co/FnheoELSzY
